ColddBox

Target IP: 10.10.131.105

Scanning



There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: HTTP and SSH. I will start my enumeration with the HTTP application, as it looks like it is running WordPress according to the scan above.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed. It mentions it is Proudly powered by WordPress.


Doing a source-code review shows the target host is running WordPress 4.1.31 version.


I performed a basic directory search and found multiple hidden directories. One being /hidden.


The /hidden page contains three usernames: c0ldd, hugo, and philip. Maybe they are they users of the WordPress application? Maybe c0ldd is the admin user?


Running wpscan with the command wpscan --url http://10.10.131.105/ --enumerate u,vt,p output the result above for the users section. It looks like there are three users in total. I did not find any vulnerable themes or plugins with this same scan. I noticed the xmlrpc.php is also enabled, so I can perform password bruteforce for all three users.


Using the command wpscan --url http://10.10.131.105 --enumerate u -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt -t 10, I cracked the password of the user c0ldd. It is 9876543210. The /wp-admin page is the login page. I should be able to login as c0ldd now.

Exploitation


I now had access to the target machine's WordPress application using the credentials c0ldd:9876543210. It looks like there are different vectors that can be used to compromise the machine. I will use a simple method by replacing the 404.php in an unused theme.


I replaced the 404.php file for the theme Twenty Fourteen with PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell script. I fired up a listener on port 8443.


To activate the exploit, I browsed to http://10.10.131.105/wp-content/themes/twentyfourteen/404.php. And I received a connection back from the target machine on my port 8443! Now I have a foothold on the machine ass www-data.

Privilege Escalation


After obtaining a foothold on the machine, I began looking. I found an interesting file called wp-config.php which contains the password cybersecurity of the user c0ldd.


I upgraded my shell to an interactive Python shell. After doing this, I switched to the user c0ldd using the pasword cybersecurity and it worked! One of the vector that can be used for PE is exploiting the lxd group.


Performing find / -perm -u=s 2>/dev/null shows the binary /usr/bin/find is exploitable.


I gained a root shell by exploiting the binary above.
